f the many medieval personal names beginning with <i>Al-</i>, especially <i>Alan</i> and <i>Alexander</i>. The Middle English hypocoristic suffix <i>-cok</i> (see   Cocke  ) was very commonly added to personal names in Middle English: compare for example   Hancock   and   Wilcock  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Allicock","meanings":["English: variant of   Alcock  ."]},{"name":"Allcock","meanings":["English: variant of   Alcock  ."]},{"name":"Cocke","meanings":["English:","nickname from Middle English <i>cok</i> (Old English and Old French <i>coc</i>) ‘rooster’.","patronymic from the Old French and Middle English personal name <i>Cok</i>, of uncertain origin but perhaps derived from the word in 1 above."]},{"name":"Alcott","meanings":["English: ostensibly a topographic name from any of a large number of places called in Old English as ‘the old cottage’ (Old English <i>(e)ald</i> + <i>cot(e)</i>). In fact, however, it is generally an altered form of   Alcock  , in part at least for euphemistic reasons.","History: Louisa May Alcott (1832–88), author of <i>Little Women</i> (1869), was the daughter of Amos Bronson Alcott (1799–1888), who had changed the surname from <i>Alcox</i>. The family trace their descent from an Alcocke family who emigrated from England to MA with John Winthrop (see   Winthrop  ) in 1630."]}]},{"name":"Edmund","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old English personal name derived from <i>ēad</i> ‘prosperity, riches’ + <i>mund</i> ‘protector’. It was borne by several early royal and saintly figures, including a 9th-century king of East Anglia killed by invading Danes, allegedly for his adherence to Christianity. In the 16th and 17th centuries, there was a good deal of interchange between <i>Edmund</i> and <i>Edward</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Edmund Alcock was born in 1386, in Badley, Suffolk, England, his father, John Alcock, was 25 and his mother, Alice Elizabeth Alrich, was 18. He had at least 1 daughter. He died in 1449, in Badley, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 63."},"et":{"1386–1449":"1386–1449","1412–1492":"1412–1492","1362–1389":"1362–1389","1369–1399":"1369–1399","1369":"1369","1412":"1412","1389":"1389","1399":"1399","1386":"1386","about 1389":"umbes 1389","1362":"1362","about 1399":"umbes 1399","1492":"1492","1449":"1449","Bosbury, Herefordshire, England":"Bosbury, Herefordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Badley, Suffolk, England":"Badley, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Ridge, Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","<Of, Badley, Suffolk, England>":"Badley, Suffolk, England"},"fi":{"1386–1449":"1386–1449","1412–1492":"1412–1492","1362–1389":"1362–1389","1369–1399":"1369–1399","1369":"1369","1412":"1412","1389":"1389","1399":"1399","1386":"1386","about 1389":"noin 1389","1362":"1362","about 1399":"noin 1399","1492":"1492","1449":"1449","Bosbury, Herefordshire, England":"Bosbury, Herefordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Badley, Suffolk, England":"Badley, Suffolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Ridge, Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","<Of, Badley, Suffolk, England>":"Badley, Suffolk, England"},"fr":{"1386–1449":"1386–1449","1412–1492":"1412–1492","1362–1389":"1362–1389","1369–1399":"1369–1399","1369":"1369","1412":"1412","1389":"1389","1399":"1399","1386":"1386","about 1389":"environ 1389","1362":"1362","about 1399":"environ 1399","1492":"1492","1449":"1449","Bosbury, Herefordshire, England":"Bosbury, Herefordshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Badley, Suffolk, England":"Badley, Suffolk, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Ridge, Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","<Of, Badley, Suffolk, England>":"Badley, Suffolk, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Edmund Alcock est né en 1386, à Badley, Suffolk, Angleterre, son père, John Alcock, avait 25 ans et sa mère, Alice Elizabeth Alrich, avait 18 ans. Il a eu au m